  <h1>Best Places to Host Your HTML File</h1>
  <p>If you want to keep your HTML file online as a document or record page, here are the best options:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Platform</th>
        <th>Pros</th>
        <th>Limitations</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr class="highlight">
        <td>GitHub Pages</td>
        <td>Free, supports custom domains, version control</td>
        <td>Requires GitHub account and basic Git knowledge</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Netlify</td>
        <td>Drag-and-drop deploy, free tier, fast CDN</td>
        <td>Slight learning curve for advanced features</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Vercel</td>
        <td>Great for static sites, Git integration</td>
        <td>Best with Git-based workflows</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Google Drive (public folder)</td>
        <td>Easy to upload and share</td>
        <td>Not ideal for full HTML rendering</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Neocities</td>
        <td>Simple, retro-style web hosting</td>
        <td>Limited storage (10MB free), basic features</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Blogspot (Blogger)</td>
        <td>Can embed HTML in posts or pages</td>
        <td>No full control over HTML files</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Recommended for You</h2>
  <p><strong>GitHub Pages</strong> – Ideal if you're comfortable with Git and want full control.</p>
  <p><strong>Netlify</strong> – Perfect for quick drag-and-drop deployment with minimal setup.</p>

